==English==

=== Alternative spelling ===
*[[color]] (U.S.)

=== Etymology ===
From Latin "color" via Old French "coulour"; in American spelling the
'u' was dropped from ''colour'' to aid in spelling. In British spelling the 'u' remains.

=== Noun ===
'''colour'''

# The spectral composition of visible light
#: ''Humans and birds can perceive colour''
# A particular set of visible spectral compositions, perceived or named as a class
#: ''Most languages have names for the colours red, blue, black and white''
# Saturated colours, as opposed to black, white or greyish colours
#: ''He referred to the white flag as one "drained of all colour"''
# Human skin tone
#: ''Colour has been a sensitive issue in many societies''
# (figuratively) interest, especially in a selective area. ''a bit of local colour.''

:''See also'' Wikipedia: [[w:color|color]]

=== Adjective ===

# Conveying colour, as opposed to shades of gray
#: ''Colour television and movies were considered a great improvement over black and white''

